<h2>Accessibility</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Media without controls and without custom UI is an accessibility violation.</strong> If you omit <code>controls</code>, you must provide a fully keyboard-accessible custom player. Users who cannot use a mouse have no way to play, pause, seek, or adjust volume otherwise.</li>
  <li>Native controls are inherently accessible: they have proper ARIA roles, keyboard support, and focus management built in by the browser.</li>
  <li>If you build a custom player, replicate all native keyboard shortcuts (space for play/pause, arrows for seek, M for mute) and provide <code>aria-label</code> values on all interactive elements.</li>
  <li>The <code>&lt;audio&gt;</code> element without <code>controls</code> is invisible and takes up no space. Screen reader users may not know it exists. Always include <code>controls</code> on audio elements unless you provide a visible custom player.</li>
</ul>

<aside>
  <h3>VB Enhancement</h3>
  <p>A future <code>&lt;media-controls&gt;</code> web component could wrap native <code>&lt;audio&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;video&gt;</code> elements with fully styled, keyboard-accessible, theme-aware controls. It would match VB's design tokens, support custom layouts, and provide consistent behavior across browsers while falling back to native controls if JavaScript fails.</p>
</aside>

<h2>Limitations</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Native control styling is browser-specific and cannot be fully customized with CSS. Pseudo-elements like <code>::-webkit-media-controls-panel</code> are non-standard and may break across versions.</li>
  <li><code>controlslist</code> hides buttons from the UI but does not prevent the underlying functionality. Users can still download the video via right-click or browser dev tools.</li>
  <li>On iOS Safari, video controls always include a fullscreen button and an AirPlay button. <code>controlslist</code> has no effect.</li>
  <li>The <code>controls</code> attribute is boolean. Writing <code>controls="false"</code> still shows controls because the attribute is present. Remove the attribute to hide them.</li>
  <li>Audio elements without <code>controls</code> collapse to zero height with no visible indication of their existence.</li>
</ul>

